    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Miklós Oláh to Tamás Nádasdy (Augsburg, 27 January 1551)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">The King is heading to Innsbruck from here for the first
                            Sunday of Lent to visit his daughters, then he will head on to Vienna
                            for 1 March. Oláh will head straight to Vienna, but he has not forgotten
                            about Bratislava either, he hopes an opportunity will arise. Márton
                            Kecseti died in poverty, he does not know how, but he does not think he
                            was on the right track. Some do not want to take on their share of the
                            common tasks and worries, but Oláh is not like that. The Queen is
                            waiting for the scions, while Oláh is waiting for an answer in the
                            matter of the late Ferenc Frangepán’s bishopric. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Spectabilis et Magnifice Domine et Frater Observandissime,
                    servitiorum meorum commendationem! </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2"><persName>Maiestas regia</persName>, dominus noster clementissimus
                    ad Dominicam Invocavit<note type="critic" xml:id="note.1">15 February.</note>
                    ibit hinc <placeName>Oenipontem</placeName>,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.2"
                        >Innsbruck.</note> magis filiarum suarum inivisendarum, quam aliarum rerum
                    gratia, deinde recta <placeName>Wiennam</placeName>, ad primum diem Martii. Ego
                    nisi vi trahar, recta hinc <placeName>Wiennam</placeName> Deo volente
                    proficiscar. De <placeName>Posonio</placeName> non obliviscar, nondum data est
                    occasio bona. <persName>Kechethi</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.3"
                        >Márton Kecseti was Tamás Szalaházy’s nephew, thanks to whom he became
                        Bishop of Veszprém between 1527 and 1548. He then resigned from the
                        bishopric and got married. He died on 13 January, 1551 in Bratislava, in
                        miserable conditions, see <hi rend="smallcap">Fazekas</hi> 2007, 33.</note>
                    pauper mortuus est, nescio, qualiter, ut audio, periculosum est <quote
                        xml:id="quote.1">aurum tangere Tolosanum</quote><note type="quote"
                        xml:id="note.quote.1">Gell. <hi rend="italic">Noct. Att.</hi>
                        3,9,7.</note><note type="critic" xml:id="note.4">This proverb refers to a
                        person who has bad luck.</note> et <quote xml:id="quote.2">equum
                        Seianum.</quote><note type="quote" xml:id="note.quote.2">Gell. <hi
                            rend="italic">Noct. Att.</hi> 3,9.</note><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.5">According to the proverb, anyone who possessed this horse
                        died, together with their entire family.</note> Mea sententia in officiis et
                    aliis omnibus regni et nostrorum omnium liberalitas inviolate semper
                    observabitur, sed quid inter tot unus? Alii ne digito quidem rem attingere aut
                    volunt, aut ex corde cogitant, ut commodi ita laboris et curae deberent esse
                    participes. Ego nihil unquam me praetermisisse memini, quod ad dignitatem
                    regiam, simul etiam nostram libertatem et permansionem pertinere fui arbitratus,
                    neque deinceps et supplicando et orando praetermittam. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">Surculos serenissima regia exspectat,<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.6">See Ep. 757.<ref>olahus.tei.15510106_1</ref></note> ego vero
                    responsum de specificatione rerum quondam fratris
                        <persName>Francisci</persName>.<note type="critic" xml:id="note.7">Ferenc
                        Frangepán, see Ep. 757. Cap. 1.<ref>olahus.tei.15510106_1</ref></note>
                    Caesarea et regia maiestates unacum regibus et principibus, laus Deo, bene
                    valent. Dominationem Vestram feliciter <del corresp="Olahus">valere opto</del>
                    cum domina <persName>coniuge</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.8"
                        >Orsolya Kanizsai.</note> sua carissima, domina mea valere opto, quibus me
                    commendo.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">Ex <placeName>Augusta</placeName> 27. Ianuarii 1551.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.5">
                    <seg type="signature">Servitor et frater Agriensis etc. manu sua.</seg>
                </p>
                <pb/>
            </div>
            <div style="handwritten" type="verso" xml:id="d.2">
                <head>On the outer side:</head>
                <p xml:id="p.6">Spectabili et magnifico domino Thomae de Nadasd perpetuo comiti
                    terrae Fogaras, iudici curiae regiae maiestatis ac regni Hungariae supremo
                    capitaneo etc. domino et fratri observandissimo.</p>
            </div>
